Title : Leon Abramson
Text : {{short description|American jazz drummer}}
'''Leon Abramson''' (born 6 January 1925 - 20 April 1992)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Feather|first1=Leonard|last2=Gitler|first2=Ira|title=The Biographical Encyclopedia of Jazz|date=2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199886401|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KEHGs88c-aAC&pg=PT33&lpg=PT33&dq=Leon+Abramson+jazz&source=bl&ots=7UF4KIdSG4&sig=YLf0JAHt59DH1yCV91ASZwshdmY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiX7Ij66JDbAhVL7oMKHXcuCj8Q6AEILzAC#v=onepage&q=Leon%20Abramson%20jazz&f=false|language=en}}</ref>, known as '''Lee Abrams''' was a [[jazz]] drummer, brother of [[Ray Abrams (musician)|Ray Abrams]], the jazz [[saxophonist]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Jewish lists: physicists and generals, actors and writers, and hundreds of other lists of accomplished Jews|author=Martin Harry Greenberg|publisher=Schocken Books|date=1979|page=159}}</ref>

==Life==
Abrams was born in [[New York City]], and was raised in [[Brooklyn]], his father played the violin and clarinet.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Jazz|others=Editor, Leonard Feather|publisher=Horizon Press, 1956|page=75}}</ref> He joined the army in 1943.  He was discharged in 1946.<ref>{{Cite book|title=60 years of recorded jazz, 1917-1977|volume=1|author=Walter Bruyninckx|publisher=Bruyninckx|page=A-10}}</ref>

He played with [[Roy Eldridge]].  On [[52nd Street]] he played with [[Coleman Hawkins]], [[Eddie Lockjaw Davis]] and [[Jay Jay Johnson]].

